<TEXT>
india and pakistan agreed wednesday to try 
to reduce military tensions in kashmir a territory over which they 
have fought two wars 
however a meeting between the foreign ministers of the two 
countries failed to make progress on the fundamental stalemate over 
kashmir 
india accuses pakistan of supporting terrorism by giving aid to 
moslem secessionists pakistan says india is violating un 
security council resolutions that call for the people of kashmir to 
determine their own future 
the ministers inder k gujral of india and sahabzada yaqubkhan 
of pakistan said the military chiefs of the two countries would 
communicate regarding ways to head off confrontations in the tense 
region 
the two also said in a joint statement that both sides would 
exercise restraint and that diplomatic channels of communication 
would be kept open 
both officials were in new york for a united nations meeting on 
international economic cooperation 
yaqubkhan told reporters afterward that the talks were free 
and frank but indicated there was no progress toward compromise 
on kashmirs future 
a 1948 security council resolution calls for a plebiscite in 
kashmir india and pakistan both agreed to the resolution but 
india holds that it was nullified when political leaders in kashmir 
opted for union with india 
more than 300 people have died in the kashmir valley in 
sectarian violence or in clashes with authorities since jan 20 
when indian security forces began a crackdown on escalating 
protests bombings and attacks on state officials 
initially the secessionists wanted union with moslem pakistan 
but in recent weeks they have declared they want an independent 
nonaligned nation in kashmir 
india and pakistan fought wars over the territory in 1948 and 
1965 india now controls the southern twothirds of jammukashmir 
and pakistan the northern third 
