<TEXT>
doctors today reported development of the first 
treatment to reduce the lungclogging secretions that make cystic 
fibrosis a major killer 
preliminary tests on adults found that a commonly used blood 
pressure medicine given in aerosol form significantly slowed lung 
damage in victims according to the report in the new england 
journal of medicine 
if it proves safe and effective in a large number of patients 
our real fantasy is that we could give it to children at an early 
age when their lungs are not damaged and it could be used as a 
preventative therapy for a long time said dr michael r 
knowles who developed the treatment 
cystic fibrosis results from a genetic defect victims lungs 
produce thick mucous that interferes with breathing and harbors 
bacteria chronic infections damage the lungs and eventually cause 
death 
only about half of all victims live to their mid20s the new 
approach if it works as doctors hope could increase life 
exponentially said dr robert beall research director of the 
cystic fibrosis foundation 
we feel that if we can change the environment of the lung so 
that we dont give bacteria a good place to live we might add 
decades to these kids lives he said 
the treatment is an inhaled form of a medicine called amiloride 
the drug known as a diuretic is ordinarily given as pills to 
treat high blood pressure congestive heart failure and fluid 
retention associated with kidney disease 
beall said another study is planned to test the therapy on 
children knowles cautioned that until the results are in doctors 
should not routinely use the drug on youngsters because it might 
have dangerous side effects 
cystic fibrosis is the most common lethal inherited genetic 
defect among whites in the united states one of every 2500 people 
has the disease 
because of the abnormality cells that line the air tubes in the 
lungs absorb too much salt and water while antibiotics are 
commonly used to reduce infections the new treatment is the first 
to tackle the underlying mixup in the bodys chemistry 
amiloride works by reducing the lung cells absorption of salt 
and water this makes their mucous thinner less likely to promote 
bacterial growth and easier for victims to cough up 
knowles study was conducted on 14 people at the university of 
north carolina 
for two consecutive sixmonth periods they used aerosol 
amiloride or a sham treatment while their conditions did not 
improve the rate of lung damage appeared to be slowed while taking 
amiloride the doctors calculated that it reduced the loss of lung 
capacity by 60 percent when compared to the dummy spray 
amiloride in pill form is ineffective against cystic fibrosis 
knowles and two other researchers hold the patent on the aerosol 
technique and the pharmaceutical firm glaxo has bought the rights 
to produce the inhaled form 
more testing will be necessary before permission is sought from 
the food and drug administration to make the treatment routinely 
available 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

