meyer and john hines of the rand corp provided a grim picture 
of a soviet military plagued by public criticism limited support 
from president mikhail s gorbachev and even a significant number 
of troops unable to speak russian 
the testimony follows us intelligence reports predicting 
continuing instability of the broader soviet economy despite 
gorbachevs efforts to institute reforms 
elsewhere on capitol hill a soviet legislator said that if his 
government fails to take immediate steps to fix the economy the 
system will collapse and spawn widespread discontent 
vladimir tikhonov an agricultural economist who is also a 
member of his countrys congress of peoples deputies told the 
joint economic committee that the soviet economy is extremely 
ill 
last weeks joint ciadefense intelligence agency report said 
the soviets cut military spending 4 percent to 5 percent last year 
strengthening the position of those in congress calling for bigger 
us defense cuts in response to changes in the soviet union and 
eastern europe 
members of congress including rep les aspin dwis chairman 
of the house armed services committee point to the recent reports 
and cia director william websters testimony as a clear argument 
for further reductions in us military spending 
aspin asked the analysts whether the soviet military could 
launch an offensive outside its borders 
they would respond but it would take a great deal of time it 
would be a relatively ineffective force and potentially one that i 
think any serious commander would not want to take into offensive 
operation hines replied 
problems for the military include the attitude of gorbachev who 
despite pleas from military officials approved student deferments 
from the armed forces 
the gorbachev regime has a deaf ear to the military meyer 
said 
the military leadership is alienated from soviet society blamed 
for the war in afghanistan and the widespread economic problems 
that plague the country he said 
in addition people in the military get paid less than the 
industrial wage work seven days a week and according to recent 
soviet statistics 170000 officers and their families are without 
housing 
complicating the militarys problems is the division between 
senior and junior officers many of the latter have sided with 
civilian reformers and joined informal ethnic groups meyer said 
about 40 percent of the soviet military are nonrussians or 
nonslavics and between 10 percent and 30 percent of them do not 
speak russian he said 
in one instance hines said a soviet commander complained that 
in his unit attached to a landbased nuclear missile project only 
two of the 40 azerbaijanis spoke russian 
the soviet ministry of defense has released figures showing 40 
percent to 70 percent of disciplinary violence is tied to 
nationalism 
the result is a mass exodus of junior officers from the 
military even under substantial economic loss to themselves said 
meyer who noted military personnel have to sign documents claiming 
they are mentally deficient or criminals to gain their release 
in addition education standards have dropped for the military 
as shown by a sharp increase in the number of accidents and deaths 
among troops using military equipment meyer said 
 
