<TEXT>
the census tries to overcome a deluge of 
criticism today returning to its roots to count americans door to 
door 
workers will hit the streets in more than 100 cities seeking to 
find and count the more than one in three households that hasnt 
been heard from yet 
the count got under way in march with the mailing of more than 
95 million questionnaires 
but mistakes in addressing meant that millions of people failed 
to get forms and millions more havent mailed theirs back the 
problems including large apartment buildings and whole blocks and 
small towns seemingly overlooked have drawn heavy criticism for 
the census bureau 
now things are moving into the next stage as census workers 
known as enumerators begin marching door to door 
in the last few decades the system of mailing out census 
questionnaires and asking people to send them back has become 
common practice it replaced the traditional but laborintensive 
process of having someone visit every home 
now the doortodoor count is reserved only for sparsely 
populated areas and for followup on people who dont answer by 
mail 
original plans had anticipated that about 70 percent of 
households would mail back their forms so far only 63 percent 
have responded and the low return rate means more hiring and more 
costs 
originally expected to cost 13 billion this year the price of 
counting americans could well increase by 150 million or more 
according to congressional sources 
in addition to problems in the mail portion of the count a 
coalition of cities and interest groups has filed suit against the 
census bureau contending that minorities are being undercounted 
and seeking to force a statistical adjustment of the final figures 
the work getting under way today covers more than 100 
metropolitan areas nationwide trying to track down people who 
either didnt get a census form or failed to mail theirs back 
individual counting expands to an additional 300 smaller 
communities on may 3 census officials report 
in rural areas that were not included in the mail portion of the 
count personal visits by census takers have been going on since 
march 
the official workers can be identified by their red white and 
blue identification badges and satchels the census bureau reported 
although the housetohouse count is now starting government 
officials continue to encourage americans to mail back forms if 
they have not done so 
counting americans on their doorsteps will continue at least 
through june and longer if needed officials said 
