<TEXT>
an environmental group says the energy 
department is planning to install a prototype of a more powerful 
submarine reactor at an upstate new york laboratory 
the natural resources defense council disclosed the plans which 
it said it learned about through declassified records of 
congressional hearings and complained wednesday that the 
government is going ahead without studying the impact on the 
environment 
the council said a prototype of the advanced fleet reactor 
would be installed at the kesselring site of the departments 
knolls atomic power laboratory near albany and schenectady ny 
the department has argued a new environmental impact statement 
is not required because one was performed for the site in 1972 for 
the reactor used to power the trident submarines said nrdc which 
was joined in its statement by a local group the knolls action 
project 
three department spokesman said wednesday night they were not 
familiar enough with the issue to comment 
the new york times reported in thursday editions that the 
department said the core of the new reactor will be tested not the 
whole reactor 
the core contains the enriched uranium fuel support elements 
and control rods that govern the nuclear reaction by absorbing 
neutrons it will be inserted in an existing reactor during the 
next two years according to the departments statement 
no commercial utility could get away with building a new 
reactor in the 1990s based on an almost 20yearold eis on a 
different reactor said dan w reicher a staff attorney for nrdc 
the advanced fleet reactor has been under development for 
several years it is designed to power the seawolf class of attack 
submarines when they are built in the mid1990s 
in budget documents submitted to congress earlier this year the 
department said the new reactor would encompass longterm 
developments now coming to fruition and will deliver more power 
more quietly than any previous submarine reactor and will do so 
without a commensurate increase in size or weight 
the department quoted declassified testimony from 1988 as saying 
the advanced fleet reactor is of the pressurized water design used 
by all other naval reactors and most of the nations civilian power 
reactors 
nrdc said the reactor most likely would be installed in a 
prototype plant that has no containment system the steel and 
concrete structure surrounding civilian reactors to confine 
radioactive material in an accident 
the department statement said there is a containment structure 
but an nrdc expert was quoted as saying it is not comparable to one 
on a civilian power plant 
