<DOCNO> AP900426-0056 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
saxophonist dexter gordon who had dazzled 
jazz audiences since the 40s with his complex bebop stylings and 
lumbering yet dignified stage presence is dead at 67 
he died wednesday of kidney failure at thomas jefferson 
university hospital where the new yorker had been admitted march 
18 with cancer of the larynx said don lucoff spokesman for blue 
note records in new york 
gordon helped define bebop in the 40s and he was the last in a 
line of saxophone geniuses that included lester young charlie 
parker and john coltrane 
he reached a new audience as the oscarnominated star of the 
1986 film round midnight and recently finished filming the 
movie awakenings with robert de niro and robin williams 
its very very difficult to even contemplate that weve lost 
such a great master of his instrument and incredible human being 
said guitarist george benson 
he was one of the true giants of the tenor saxophone 
fluegelhorn player art farmer said from his home in vienna he 
was an inspiration to me although i didnt play saxophone going 
back over 40 years 
drummer art blakey performing in seattle said he and gordon 
played together in one of the early billy eckstine bands and he 
played on one of gordons last albums 
he called me last week wanted me to see him i thought he was 
coming back to new york blakey said gonna miss him 
gordons style was his own but his life bore tragic similarities 
to the other jazz greats exile bouts of drug and alcohol abuse a 
stint in prison on drug charges 
gordon combined youngs melodic approach with the harddriving 
sound and complex harmonics of coleman hawkins and parker at a 
sets end he would hold out his horn as if presenting it to the 
audience for a share of the applause 
gordon went to europe in 1962 for a threemonth tour and ended 
up staying for 14 years first in paris then denmark 
i met him in europe in a jazz club in copenhagen benson 
recalled they called him i think it was correct king gordon 
dexter his music was always par excellence 
it was those years as an expatriate that led director bertrand 
tavernier to cast gordon in round midnight the bittersweet 
tale of an american jazz musician in paris and an admiring french 
fan 
the film was loosely based on the life of pianist bud powell but 
had many parallels with gordons and with those of many jazz 
artists who fled bigotry and rough times in america for europe in 
the 1950s and 60s 
the 6foot5 gordon who dominated the film with his smoky 
voice smooth sax playing and worldweary yet regal bearing was 
nominated for an academy award a first for a musician 
the story is so personal i dont mean dexter gordon but this 
long line of musicians who have been underappreciated and 
swindled he said in 1986 
the film sparked new interest in his career which began in the 
1930s when he went to jazz concerts with his father a los angeles 
physician whose patients included duke ellington and lionel hampton 
gordon performed in clubs as a teenager and soon played with 
the big bands of hampton louis armstrong and eckstine 
his mentors were young and herschel evans and he refined the 
innovations parker had laid down gordon in turn helped shape the 
style and music of coltrane and sonny rollins 
he left eckstine to work on 52nd street the jazz capital in 
new york performing with parker miles davis powell and max 
roach and recording with dizzy gillespie 
by the late 40s he was fronting his own groups he and his 
style of music faded from view in the 50s during which he served 
two years in prison in california on drug charges after prison he 
recorded five acclaimed albums for blue note from 1961 to 1965 
among his more highly regarded albums are long tall dexter 
the savoy sessions doin alright dexter calling our 
man in paris and a swingin affair 
gordon was survived by his wife maxine two daughters and three 
sons 
a memorial was planned for may 6 in new york lucoff said 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

