ministers with broad control over the economy and local governments 
during the period of the embargo ms dapkus said 
the powers include the ability to change supply plans transfer 
workers to different jobs and use natural and financial resources 
in a centralized manner she said 
effects of the embargo mounted hospitals running low on 
medicine discouraged all but emergency surgery radio vilnius 
reported in addition newspapers prepared to cut back the size of 
their editions by as much as half 
