aerial pesticide spraying to attack an infestation 
of mediterranean fruit flies in one southern florida county began 
today after a threehour delay caused by equipment problems 
a helicopter loaded with syrupy insect bait spiked with the 
pesticide malathion took off at midmorning for up to seven hours of 
spraying over parts of dade county said phyllis habeck 
spokeswoman for the eradication task force in miami 
the helicopter had been airborne shortly after sunrise but 
quickly returned after spray nozzles clogged she said 
agriculture commissioner doyle conner ordered the spraying in 
dade county to protect floridas 14 billion citrus industry 
in southern california which is also waging a battle against 
the pest a federal judge ruled wednesday that malathion spraying 
to eradicate the medfly does not violate environmental aviation or 
pesticide laws 
