<TEXT>
this time it really is the end of the line a 
chorus line broadways longest running show plays its 6137th 
and final performance saturday night 
the evening a benefit for the new york shakespeare festival 
has a top ticket price of 500 and the 1483seat shubert theater 
has been sold out for weeks the last performance promises to be an 
event especially with most of the original cast in the audience 
and possibly on stage at the finale and it will be a celebration 
and remembrance of michael bennett the man behind the musical who 
died of aids in 1987 at age 44 
in a funny way we all felt the show wasnt going to close 
said tom porter who probably has seen the broadway production more 
than anybody but now were beginning to realize it certainly is 
going to happen and ill miss it when the show closes there 
wont be a michael bennett musical on broadway 
porter the musicals production stage manager has been with 
a chorus line for more than 12 years first with the chicago 
company for eight months and then in new york from a spot in the 
back of the house or by watching a television monitor in his 
backstage office he keeps an eye on each performance 
a chorus line tells the stories of 17 dancers who compete 
for eight roles in a big broadway musical it was bennetts baby 
born out of more than 40 hours of taped conversations by broadway 
dancers who talked about their lives loves hopes and fears 
during an extended series of workshops at the new york 
shakespeare festival bennett conceived the show hiring nicholas 
dante and james kirkwood to fashion the book from the tapes marvin 
hamlisch to write the music and ed kleban the lyrics 
the show which arrived at the shubert on july 25 1975 after 
performances at the shakespeare festival offbroadway was an 
immediate hit more than 65 million people have paid 150 million 
to see the musical on broadway the show which also has been 
performed in more than 20 countries has made 38 million in net 
profit for the festival 
but grosses have been dwindling and the show incurred heavy 
losses last january joseph papp head of the shakespeare festival 
announced feb 21 that the show would end its 15year run the 
following month it set off a boxoffice stampede with grosses 
doubling to nearly 400000 a week the original closing date 
march 31 was extended by four weeks 
the extension enabled the show to do a special benefit on april 
8 bennetts birthday which raised more than 50000 for equity 
fights aids 
it was an emotional night porter recalled the dancers 
went back to their dressing rooms changed their clothes and the 
audience was still on its feet applauding 
in the weeks since papp announced the closing the news media 
have descended on the shubert 
i think we started outdoing the statue of liberty in terms of 
visitors said porter 
television crews some from as far away as sweden and japan 
were nightly visitors original cast members sang and cried on phil 
donahues and geraldo riveras tv talk shows current performers in 
the show were profiled on nightline with ted koppel 
the musical spawned four books in the last year including a 
biography of bennett by boston globe theater critic kevin kelly and 
on the line remembrances by members of the original cast 
according to ken mandelbaum author of a chorus line and the 
musicals of michael bennett the musicals main legacy is the way 
it was put together through the workshops 
from then on almost every musical that got to broadway went 
through some form of workshop mandelbaum said when the 
workshop of a chorus line started there was no script really and 
no songs they went into rehearsal to create the show 
today he added most directors and producers of musicals dont 
use workshops as effectively as bennett did they use them mostly 
as additional auditions or as extra rehearsals 
a chorus line also represents broadway in a way that 
probably no other show did mandelbaum added no other musical 
was so about broadway and as it traveled around the country 
people really got that feeling 
