<TEXT>
unexpected strength in the us economy has 
led many analysts to double their estimates of growth for the first 
part of the year some pegging it as high as 3 percent rather than 
the puny 1 percent they thought earlier 
but some economists noting continued high interest rates as 
well as the warm weather and other special factors pushing growth 
so far this year say the pace cannot be sustained 
and inflation running hotter than expected is also a worry 
the gross national product the nations output of goods and 
services grew 3 percent in 1989 but had slowed to a rate of 11 
percent in the final quarter of the year the figures for the first 
three months of 1990 will be released friday 
where many private economists had predicted growth of between 1 
percent and 15 percent for the januarymarch period they now 
foresee an increase between 2 percent and 25 percent some believe 
it could be as high as 3 percent 
while opinions differ on the growth rate during the rest of this 
year there is virtual unanimity that the federal reserve has 
achieved its soft landing slowing the economy without tipping 
it into a recession 
but the central bank so far has not been able to achieve the 
goal that made it want to slow things down in the first place 
holding back price increases inflation rose from 46 percent in 
1989 to an annual rate of 85 percent in the first quarter of 1990 
as measured by the labor departments consumer price index 
the weather that helped propel business growth also pushed up 
prices especially for food and energy although they have since 
moderated 
at the same time the stronger economy created about 726000 
jobs during the first three months of 1990 driving unemployment 
down to 52 percent its lowest rate in a year 
