us negotiators announced today that they 
have reached basic agreement on a new trade accord with the soviet 
union that would normalize trade relations between the two 
countries for the first time in nearly a half century 
us deputy trade representative julius katz the leader of the 
us negotiating team said fundamentally we have reached 
agreement on the text of the new pact 
he said that the exact language still needed to be worked out on 
four minor issues but he did not believe they would pose an 
obstacle to signing a final document when president bush meets 
soviet president mikhail gorbachev in washington from may 30 to 
june 3 
as far as i am concerned we have substantial agreement and i 
do not see an obstacle to its signature at the time of the 
summit katz said in a telephone conference call 
he spoke to reporters in washington after the end of thursdays 
negotiating session in paris the discussions were allowed to 
continue this week after bush decided against imposing economic 
sanctions on the soviet union because of its crackdown in lithuania 
bush on tuesday announced that he was not imposing any 
sanctions ending days of debate inside the administration over 
whether the economic talks with the soviets should be cancelled in 
an effort to bring pressure to bear on gorbachev to seek a 
negotiated settlement of the lithuanian situation 
even after all the minor issues have been cleared up the new 
economic agreement cannot be signed by bush until he certifies that 
the soviet union is allowing free emigration of soviet jews and 
other dissidents from the country 
