<TEXT>
the legislature has overwhelmingly 
approved a campaignreform package that its supporters hope will be 
a model for similar legislation in congress 
the elections and ethics reform act of 1990 which sets 
voluntary spending limits and provides public financing for 
congressional races cleared the house on wednesday by 1280 the 
senate sent the bill to gov rudy perpich for his signature on a 
vote of 611 
perpich said hes inclined to sign the bill 
the bill also prohibits state lawmakers from soliciting campaign 
contributions from lobbyists during legislative sessions expands 
lobbyist disclosure requirements requires the legislature to 
conduct its business in public and establishes a new screening 
process for judicial appointments 
supporters say minnesota is the first state to enact such 
legislation 
people everywhere are frustrated with the excessive influence 
that money plays in politics today especially when it comes to the 
united states congress said state house speaker robert vanasek 
we will be sending the strongest possible message to congress 
that the time has come for congress to mend its ways and enact 
campaign finance reform on its own said vanasek of the 
democraticfarmerlabor party which controls the house and senate 
the way to get the federal government moving again is to end 
the money monopoly that has weakened our elections and made the 
voters cynical and turned off when election time comes he said 
many independentrepublicans said they saw the reform package as 
a step in the right direction and voted for it despite reservations 
that it may be found unconstitutional ben ginsburg chief legal 
counsel for the national republican committee has said if the 
campaign finance provisions become law they will be challenged 
the bill sets voluntary spending limits of 425000 for us 
house candidates and 34 million for us senate hopefuls 
effective jan 1 
if both major party candidates for an office agreed to abide by 
the limits neither would receive taxpayer subsidies if one 
candidate agreed and the other did not the candidate who limits 
expenditures would receive public financing of up to 25 percent of 
the limit established for the office they seek 
under a 1974 state law candidates for the legislature and state 
constitutional offices including governor receive a partial 
public subsidy if they agree to accept spending limits 
the bill also reinstates a state income tax credit for 
contributions to political parties and to state and federal 
candidates who agree to abide by spending limits under the bill 
individuals can claim a credit equal to contributions of 50 or 
less and couples can claim a credit equal to contributions of 100 
or less 
