defense secretary dick cheney proposed today 
to sharply reduce the pentagon plan to purchase 132 b2 stealth 
bombers to 75 planes as he unveiled a package of aircraft cutbacks 
designed to save 348 billion through 1997 
testifying before the house armed services committee cheney 
said the changes were warranted because nato faces fewer enemy 
aircraft and a reduced ground threat as a result of the dramatic 
changes sweeping eastern europe and the soviet union 
but committee chairman les aspin dwis told reporters after 
the morning session that cheneys reductions may not placate the 
budget cutting ardor on capitol hill 
he faulted cheneys program contending it was still based on 
an unrealistically pessimistic view of the soviet threat 
cheneys blueprint follows a detailed pentagon study of military 
needs and came one day after an army official said troop levels 
would probably be cut by 250000 over the next five or six years 
he was scheduled to testify later in the afternoon before the 
senate armed services committee 
the proposed reductions in aircraft would also affect the size 
of the navy in answer to a question from aspin cheney said 
reducing the number of a12 attack planes could mean elimination of 
two of the navys 14 aircraft carrier battle groups 
the defense secretary testified that his plans would trim 241 
billion from earlier estimates of pentagon spending plans for 1991 
and 348 billion through 1997 cheney offered his plan at the same 
time the democraticcontrolled house and senate are drafting 
spending blueprints for 1991 expected to call for sharp cuts in 
pentagon spending 
the proposal drew mixed reactions from members of the armed 
services committee 
let me tell you where i think this proposal is in trouble 
said rep john kasich rohio and an opponent of the b2 bomber 
were cutting a little bit and were stretching a lot and 
when you cut and stretch you drive up the cost 
