<TEXT>
the labor department on thursday promised 
quick new safety rules for the petrochemical industry in an effort 
to prevent disasters such as last years phillips explosion that 
killed 23 workers in texas 
the occupational safety and health administration plans to 
establish the new safety guidelines by the end of the summer the 
agency said in a report to president bush outlining causes of the 
oct 23 blast at the plant in pasadena a houston suburb another 
130 workers were injured 
the probe showed the explosion could have been prevented through 
better safety procedures and that it demonstrated the need for 
mandatory safety rules at plants that use and store highly 
flammable liquids and chemicals the report said 
the investigation of the phillips catastrophe has caused osha 
to take stock and consider a strong course of action to prevent 
such disasters the report said 
phillips petroleum co has said its own investigation showed 
company safety procedures were not followed it plans to appeal at 
least part of the 57 million in fines osha proposed last week for 
alleged willful safety violations 
phillips is eager to review any recommendations osha can offer 
that will further improve the safety of our operations the 
bartlesville oklabased company said in a statement thursday 
most of oshas new requirements will be fundamental safety 
procedures that many firms already are following said gerard 
scannell assistant labor secretary in charge of osha 
the mandatory safety guidelines which would affect about 2300 
petrochemical plants nationwide would include requiring companies 
to analyze hazards in the workplace ensure equipment works 
properly train and inform employees on hazards and develop 
emergency response procedures scannell said 
the agency is required to review public comment on the proposed 
rules so it could be up to a year before they take effect 
ct roberts a phillips employee at the texas plant who was off 
duty when the blast occurred said the new osha guidelines are long 
overdue 
the only way these companies are going to take safety 
seriously is to be pushed into it said roberts who was in 
washington for an aflcio event to spotlight attention on workplace 
injuries and deaths 
osha also will consider revising the way it sets priorities for 
inspections and devoting more attention to the petrochemical 
industry scannell said 
right now osha allocates resources according to a priority 
system based primarily on industry injury rates the report to bush 
said osha may start considering other factors as well such as the 
potential risk to workers 
historically the petrochemical industry has had a lower injury 
rate than other industries the report said but it noted that 
major disasters have occurred recently in the industry including 
the 1984 disaster in bhopal india where a deadly chemical release 
killed more than 2000 people and in mexico city where an 
explosion of liquified petroleum killed about 650 
sectors of the petrochemical industry with a high potential for 
fire explosion or catastrophic release include those involving 
plastics synthetic rubber and petroleum refining the report said 
oshas investigation into the texas blast showed that four 
highly flammable gases escaped from an open valve forming a huge 
vapor cloud that traveled through the plant within seconds under 
high pressure 
a series of explosions occurred after the cloud came in contact 
with an unidentified ignition source 
contrary to phillips own procedures as well as standard 
industry practice there was no backup protection such as a double 
valve to protect against valve failure or protect against an 
untimely valve opening scannell said 
