civil liberties groups on thursday demanded 
tighter control of britains mi5 intelligence service after the 
23nation council of europe found it guilty of breaching human 
rights 
in a ruling this week the west european nations censured mi5 
for spying on two former officers of the british national council 
for civil liberties in the 1970s and classifying them and their 
organization as subversives 
the councils court the european court of human rights based in 
strasbourg france has found britain guilty more often than any 
other country 
the latest ruling sparked a new dispute over what critics see as 
a warping of civil liberties in britain and resistance to reform by 
prime minister margaret thatcher 
charter 88 a pressure group that includes retired judges 
academics and politicians said the ruling underlined the need for 
britain to have a written constitution and bill of rights 
one of the people classified as subversive and a communist 
sympathizer harriet harman is now a senior legislator in the 
opposition labor party and likely to become a cabinet minister if 
the socialists win the next election 
the other patricia hewitt was press secretary to labor party 
leader neil kinnock in the 1980s 
the two women demanded thursday that mi5 destroy files it 
presumably has amassed on them through surveillance including 
suspected phone taps 
ms harman said the surveillance casts a shadow over me which 
is totally unjustified and which i bitterly resent 
i want my file destroyed she said at a news conference at 
the house of commons 
she urged that mi5 and mi6 which gathers intelligence abroad 
should be directly accountable to parliament in the style of the 
us central intelligence agency 
the demand was echoed by the civil liberties council and 
legislators from both parties who consider current controls too 
lax 
the government made no comment in accordance with its practice 
of refusing to discuss the security services 
according to leaks to british newspapers mi5 has removed the 
civil liberties council from its classified list 
the government has also said it has rectified the human rights 
charge with a 1989 security service act 
this laid out a charter for mi5 for the first time provided for 
a complaints tribunal for people who suspect they are under 
surveillance and it required agents to get a cabinet ministers 
approval to bug or break into buildings 
but mi5 continues to report only to the prime minister and 
another cabinet minister the home secretary not parliament 
mi5 has been accused in recent years of infringing civil 
liberties by tapping telephones of labor union activists and 
antinuclear campaigners according to the memoirs of a retired 
agent peter wright mi5 tried to destabilize the labor government 
of harold wilson in the 60s and the 70s 
britain has been convicted of 22 violations of the european 
human rights convention including several on issues related to 
northern ireland such as nojury trials and imprisonment of 
terrorists 
britains frequent runins result partly from the fact that it 
is the only country in western europe that has no written bill of 
rights or constitution 
human rights issues are automatically transferred to the 
european court instead of being filtered through domestic courts 
the nearest thing in britain to a constitution is a 1689 
declaration accepted by william iii that ensured the ascendancy of 
parliamentary power over royal power 
