<TEXT>
poverty and despair facing many american 
children are not only personal tragedies but a staggering 
national tragedy that threatens americas future a federal 
commission reported thursday 
the national commission on children said in an interim report 
that children have become the poorest age group in the united 
states with one child in five living below the poverty level 
it said the childhood poverty more than any other factor places 
young americans at risk for a range of longterm problems 
including poor health failure in school teenage pregnancy crime 
and drugs 
as a result it said many of todays children will reach 
adulthood unhealthy illiterate and unemployable 
the health and vitality of our economy and our democracy are 
increasingly in danger sen jay rockefeller dwva chairman 
of the panel said in releasing the report 
these are personal tragedies rockefeller said they are 
also a staggering national tragedy 
at the white house press secretary marlin fitzwater said we 
have very deep concerns about the children of this country and the 
poverty level that they may be facing we know this problem 
exists 
he added its always constructive to get the best kind of 
analysis we can over how deep and how wide this problem is 
the commission was established by congress and its members were 
appointed by the president and house and senate leaders it made no 
recommendations in its interim report which was required by law 
but its findings are expected to form the basis for suggestions for 
new spending next year 
at a news conference with other members of the commission 
rockefeller acknowledged the recommendations likely will be 
expensive but commission members said the recommendations will 
involve efforts by business and families as well as government and 
are needed to head off future costs to society 
we know these kids are going to cost us billions in the 
future if not helped said dr t berry brazelton professor of 
pediatrics at harvard university theyre going to be the 
terrorists of the future 
in the report rockefeller said it is a tragic irony that at a 
time of prosperity the united states seems to be failing its 
children 
the evidence of this failure is pervasive he said the 
seriousness of the problems afflicting many of the nations 
children and their families is now largely beyond debate 
the report cited an array of jarring statistics all of them 
previously reported about childhood poverty 
malnutrition affects nearly a halfmillion children and 
100000 children are homeless 
among black and hispanic children poverty is even worse the 
poverty rate in 1987 the year the report cited was 15 percent for 
white children but 45 percent for black children and 39 percent for 
hispanic children 
one of every four rural child is poor and rural families are 
less likely than urban ones to receive public assistance 
us children on average are economically better off now than 
they were in the 1960s primarily due to rising family incomes 
through 1973 and the trend toward smaller families it said but 
those figures do not reflect the growing disparity among families 
the report said 
the 20 percent of children living in a poor family was up from 
15 percent in 1970 it said 
