<TEXT>
a powerful earthquake on thursday killed more 
than 100 people and damaged hundreds of homes in a remote region of 
central china populated mainly by tibetan herders officials said 
the quake thursday evening measured 69 on the richter scale 
striking hainan tibetan autonomous prefecture in qinghai province 
about 900 miles southwest of beijing a state seismology bureau 
said friday 
a bureau official who did not give his name said 109 people 
were killed and 120 were hospitalized more than 1000 homes in the 
sparsely populated rugged area collapsed from the initial quake 
and more than 500 aftershocks he said 
aftershocks as strong as 5 on the richter scale were felt in the 
provincial capital of xining about 70 miles northeast of hainan 
prefecture and in lanzhou a city 180 miles the east 
the official xinhua news agency said homes in heka township of 
xinghai county were damaged and a landslide occurred at the 
longyangxia reservoir on the yellow river a hydroelectric power 
station at the reservoir was not damaged it said 
the richter scale is a gauge of the energy released by a quake 
as measured by the ground motion recorded on a seismograph a quake 
measuring 6 can cause severe damage in a populated area and one 
measuring 7 is 10 times stronger and can cause widespread heavy 
damage 
qinghai is a mountainous region inhabited by miners and herders 
where quakes occur fairly frequently with few casualties a quake 
measuring 67 struck the region in january damaging some buildings 
but causing no casualties 
the far western chinese province of xinjiang was hit by a quake 
measuring 64 on april 19 about 1300 homes were damaged but only 
two people were injured 
