<TEXT>
since the revolution the museum for german 
history in east berlin is putting more truth and less distortion 
into its exhibits covering events of the last 1500 years 
huge chunks of the berlin wall stand in the courtyard as part of 
a new display about the peaceful uprising that reversed four 
decades of stalinist rule less than six months ago an exhibit 
glorified the walls construction in 1961 
museum officials have closed the section covering east germanys 
history from its founding in 1949 which was redone just before the 
dramatic political events of autumn 1989 
they seem embarrassed by their collection of everything from the 
office furnishings of the former communist rulers to clothing and 
dishes produced at the first staterun enterprises 
in the section on the period from the end of world war ii to the 
nations founding is a new panel acknowledging the museums guilt 
and responsibility for a display that as we know today 
permitted no active living relation to history and the present 
dr kurt paetzold a history professor at humboldt university in 
east berlin is offering a course this spring called historical 
thinking and history teaching in the crises of our time 
there is a need for a course like that he said in an 
interview you cant teach as if nothing happened 
a new west german guidebook claims the exhibit beginning in 1949 
was closed because it offered an all too euphoric view of east 
german history 
the display on the revolution opened april 12 has a collection 
of banners and posters carried by protesters in prodemocracy 
marches 
visitors have snapped up sets of postcards with the most famous 
slogans already sold out is a picture featuring the wide grin and 
large teeth of egon krenz the first successor to erich honecker 
the leader ousted in october 
poor sellers include a book titled lenin in berlin and 
postcards of the soviet army supplying east germany with food from 
the soviet union 
despite the tacit apology in the 194549 section the communist 
states creation still is called a wonder in the history of the 
german people and europe the communist party which now has 
changed its name is portrayed as incorporating the best traditions 
of german history 
this is unbelievable said klaus geberts a retired factory 
worker from west berlin on his first visit to the museum 
one can even laugh its not forbidden anymore he said 
inspecting a collection of hand tools that belonged to wilhelm 
pieck first president of east germany 
this museum wont be here much longer geberts predicted 
entries in the guest book indicate however that many visitors 
believe the exhibits should remain as they are 
leave everything as it is and build a new one with whole 
truth wrote andreas kiest who identified himself as a schoolboy 
from west germany 
werner fuehrer wrote this museum is also part document leave 
it as is 
a swedish history teacher wrote in imperfect english please 
save this exhibition for the future it is itself a monument of to 
lie with the help of history 
the marxist viewpoint permeates exhibits from the middle ages to 
1949 
medieval conflicts between peasants and rich craftsmen are 
portrayed as an example of class warfare the defeat of 
imperial germany in world war i was made possible the exhibit 
says by the efforts of the working class 
no mention is made of the molotovribbentrop pact of 1939 
secret provisions of which divided the independent baltic states 
and much of poland between nazi germany and the soviet union 
</TEXT>
