<DOCNO> AP900426-0202 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
the heightening drama over saving 
floridas dying everglades has cast new villains the farmers and 
dairymen who work the land around giant lake okeechobee 
environmentalists say agriculture causes too much pollution in 
the precious okeechobee which provides water for the vast wetlands 
of the everglades and the cities of the crowded coast some argue 
its time to return the land to the wilderness it was before the 
ranchers and farmers came about a century ago 
the first thing we have to do is get rid of the sugar cane 
south of lake okeechobee then we have to get rid of the dairy 
cattle on the north side said marjory stoneman douglas an 
environmental activist who has fought for much of her 100 years to 
preserve the everglades system 
us attorney dexter lehtinen whos filed suit seeking to force 
the state to increase protection of the everglades has said that 
if farmers cant reduce pollution its an easy choice save the 
glades and let agriculture move to wisconsin 
farmers feel theyre politically expedient scapegoats they say 
theyre threatened by environmental experimentation that has only 
one sure result a big bill for stateordered programs to cut 
pollution 
i dont think its fair said david beardsley a 
fourthgeneration farmer near clewiston its our land were 
interested in our home as much as anybody else but i think were 
an easy target 
the nutrientladen pollutants that run off the farms and dairies 
feed unnatural growth of some plants in the everglades choking 
waterways and disrupting the systems food chain 
at the same time the heavy development of south florida has 
disrupted rain patterns and the flow of water into the everglades 
drying up parts of the system 
residents of the region feel the environmental damage most are 
under some form of water rationing and may soon face stricter 
limits smoke from wildfires in the everglades last year closed 
highways and caused respiratory problems 
gov bob martinez says the environment ranks with crime and 
drugs as floridas top issues 
the environmental concerns of floridians coalesced in the 
adoption of a save our everglades plan in 1983 its aim is 
making the everglades look and function more as it did at the 
beginning of the century 
in 1900 there were no big farms which disrupt natural water 
flow use water then discharge pollutants back into the everglades 
system nor did 45 million people live on the condominiumdotted 
gold coast from palm beach to miami sucking huge quantities of 
water from the system 
sugar growers fare worse than the dairies in their public image 
of governmentsubsidized millionaires who exploit foreign cane 
cutters and the environment twothirds of the sugar cane land 
belongs to us sugar corp or companies owned by the cubanborn 
fanjul family invariably described as sugar barons 
more than 100 other farmers work land in the 700000acre 
everglades agricultural area south of the lake however some 
413000 acres are in sugar cane the rest in winter vegetables like 
lettuce celery cabbage and carrots 
beardsleys family started farming when his greatgrandfather 
came to okeechobee before world war i and saw the newly drained 
land rich in decomposed vegetation 
they just went wild when they saw the dark rich muck he 
said 
land was cleared by hand and boats were the only means of 
transport for years fires and floods from hurricanes made 
okeechobee farming highly risky until the army corps of engineers 
began building an extensive drainage and canal system five decades 
ago 
about 1960 decreased sugar production in other us growing 
areas resulted in higher domestic quotas florida farmers planted 
more cane the us economic embargo against cuba cut sugar 
imports and soon florida was the nations no 1 cane producer 
moving north along the lake the sweet smoke of the sugar mills 
and fields of tall cane give way to stretches of flat pasture 
dotted with grazing cattle 
at mcarthur farms manager kent bowen shows off the farms 4 
million experiment to cut pollution from 9000 head of cattle 
wastecollecting barns with concrete floors 
beef cattle have been in the area since the 19th century 
frederic remington sketched its cattle ranges in the 1890s but 
dairy operations didnt arrive until the 1960s when land prices 
skyrocketed along the coast 
dairy cattle are fed extra phosphorous to enrich their milk for 
humans but too much of it reaches their waste and taints waterways 
that feed okeechobee 
reducing the waste flow has proved too costly for some small 
operations at least 14 of the areas 47 dairy operations are 
accepting a state offer to move to lesssensitive land 602 a 
head to get out of town 
that will cost the water district and state more than 5 million 
to move 9500 cattle a 20 percent cut in the okeechobee dairy 
population that has produced about a fourth of floridas milk 
mcarthur farms plans to stay weve looked at north florida 
and georgia but this is a pretty good place to dairy its near 
the best milk market in florida bowen said 
bob butler whose dairy has 2200 adult cattle said pollution 
control will cost his farm about 564000 for fencing and catchment 
systems mandated by the state 
were realizing that we have a problem and were trying to 
come in and take care of our problems on our own he said 
environmentalists give the dairy farmers good marks for effort 
but say the sugar growers are flunking 
the everglades coalition an umbrella organization of 
conservation groups plans to lobby for an end to federal import 
quotas and other indirect subsidies that keep the sugar growers 
profitable 
george wedgworth president of the sugar cane growers 
cooperative for three decades says the environmental goals for 
okeechobee are unrealistic because of the vast artificial system 
built to support agriculture and protect residents from flooding 
its not a natural system anymore he said pointing to a 
map of the dikes and canals you cant turn the clock back 
sugar growers levied their own environmental tax last year 
assessing 5 an acre to finance environmental studies 
conservationists contend its just a delaying action 
many of us have been out here a lifetime wedgworth said 
were going to be sure we have the right technical answers to the 
problems were not going to be distracted by the hysterics of the 
time 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

