<TEXT>
pope john paul ii is making another trip to 
latin america where the roman catholic church has changed 
dramatically in the 11 years since he first outlined his vision of 
its role 
the nineday visit to mexico starting sunday will underline 
the changes since 1979 when john paul set the tone of his papacy 
toward church activism in the overwhelmingly roman catholic region 
maintain your commitment to the poor the pope told his bishops 
in puebla mexico but do not become partisan politicians 
in the ensuing years the church has assumed a greater role in 
social and economic affairs and gained broader prestige in latin 
america but divisions have emerged between liberal and 
conservative clergy 
from without the church is increasingly threatened by the 
aggressive proselytizing of evangelical protestant churches 
it is challenged by the dramatic growth of poverty in a region 
of vital concern to the vatican this is john pauls 10th trip to 
latin america and he also plans to visit cuba perhaps in december 
latin americans make up nearly half the worlds 850 million 
catholics the latin church has influenced catholicism worldwide 
with its bold efforts to adapt the gospel to third world societies 
liberation theology which links spiritual freedom to liberation 
from economic and social oppression was born in latin ameria john 
paul has sought to blunt the philosophys effect 
certainly what i feel in the last few years is what we feel a 
little in the universal church it is a moment of what some call 
conservatism said the rev irineu wilges a brazilian who is the 
franciscan orders counselor for latin america 
despite that conservatism the latin american church leadership 
has transformed itself 
cardinals and bishops once close to the ruling minority began 
condemning political repression in the 1970s when brutal 
dictatorships were common frequently the church was the only 
institution strong enough to stand up to the government 
catholic officials who specialize in latin america say the 
church leadership has extended its political role in three ways 
encouraging the establishment of democracy particularly in 
brazil and chile 
serving as a mediator between the government and guerrillas as 
in nicaragua and el salvador 
speaking out on problems facing new fragile democracies such 
as land reform foreign debt and the rights of native indians 
those actions reflect the churchs widespread credibility in 
latin america and its effort to grow closer to the poor 
the people have much more faith in the church than they did 10 
years ago said the rev jose luis castaneda a peruvian who is 
the jesuit orders regional assistant for south america i dont 
know if its the merit of the church or the disasters of the 
politicians 
john paul has supported the latin churchs option for the 
poor declared at a 1968 conference of bishops in medellin 
colombia 
on trips to the region the pope has assailed dictatorship 
highlighted the foreign debt problem and defended labor unions he 
also has condemned liberation theology that uses marxist analysis 
and warned clerics to stay out of politics 
action has accompanied his words particuarly in brazil whose 
bishops have encouraged liberation theology brazil has about 
100000 ecclesiastical base communities churchsponsored 
groups that press for political and social change 
the vatican promoted conservatives in brazil which has moved 
the bishops conference to a more centrist position 
in 1985 it ordered the rev leonardo boff brazils most 
prominent progressive theologian to maintain obedient silence 
for a year 
last year the vatican divided the paolo archdiocese of another 
progressive cardinal paulo evaristo arns into five smaller 
dioceses seriously diminishing his influence 
it isnt that some people are for helping the poor and some 
are against wilges said the church is divided over how to do 
it 
divisions between liberals and progressives have deepened 
because of the actions in brazil and similar ones in other 
countries 
last year the vatican ignored the choice of the organizations 
own leadership in choosing a new secretarygeneral of the latin 
american confederation of religious prompting an outcry from 
priests and nuns 
religious orders account for about 80 percent of the priests and 
nuns in latin america their members tend to be more liberal than 
diocesan clergy and bishops 
the vatican acted after the confederation introduced a 
biblestudy program for members that the congregation for the 
doctrine of the faith condemned as too ideological 
whatever the internal problems many church officials say latin 
american catholicisms greatest challenge is from conservative 
evangelical churches on the outside 
noncatholics in the region now number more than 30 million the 
latin american bishops conference says 
in mexico the number of protestants grew more than 500 percent 
in 19501980 to 22 million according to church figures in some 
mexican states up to 20 percent of the people are believed to be 
noncatholic 
some catholic officials contend the churchs approach to faith 
has been too political or intellectual others claim the 
evangelical churches receive money from the us government or 
businesses hoping to hinder church efforts for social change 
officials say greater poverty and evergrowing urban slums 
create serious problems for the church in spreading its message 
activism on behalf of the poor continues to exact a price as shown 
by the murder of six jesuits by salvadoran soldiers in november 
the standard of living is lamentably regressive bishop 
dario castrillon hoyos president of the bishops conference said 
in a recent report 
we must therefore ask ourselves what have been the results of 
the churchs effort to raise peoples consciences and of the 
political commitment of catholics 
