<TEXT>
lawton chiles compared himself to abraham 
lincoln when he told floridians he was being treated for 
depression but he may be more like tom eagleton and that bodes 
well for his gubernatorial prospects 
eagleton was forced off the democrats 1972 presidential ticket 
after disclosures that hed had shock treatment for depression but 
two years later missouri voters reelected him to the senate by a 
landslide 
like eagleton chiles is wellknown and wellliked in his state 
and that familiarity analysts say is key to how voters treat 
candidates who have acknowledged problems such as mental illness 
drug abuse and alcoholism 
tom kiley an adviser to democratic presidential nominee michael 
dukakis in 1988 and to eagleton in his 1974 senate race said such 
troubles are a legitimate campaign issue because they bear on 
questions of judgment but they can be blown out of proportion when 
voters dont know a candidate well he said 
when people are familiar with a politician its a lot easier 
for them to weigh the information put it in context and come to a 
conclusion about the role it should play in an election kiley 
said 
rumors of depression swirled briefly around dukakis shortly 
after he became the democratic presidential nominee he suffered 
considerable damage by failing to squelch them promptly largely 
because he was new on the national scene 
people had no longterm familiarity and personal information 
to fall back on kiley said 
that is not the case with chiles who served three senate terms 
before quitting in 1988 he blamed burnout and frustration 
but leaving the capital didnt cure his blue moods insomnia and 
lack of appetite only when chiles started taking prozac a common 
medication for depression did his spirits rise and his political 
drive return 
chiles entered the florida governors race this month and became 
the instant favorite over both rep bill nelson his chief rival in 
the democratic primary and incumbent gop gov bob martinez polls 
showed him the clear leader even after people were told he was 
taking medication for depression 
other candidates have been raising questions about chiles 
mental state both indirectly and headon if lawton is depressed 
sitting 18 years in committee meetings in washington if he spends 
about 13 minutes in the governors chair he may blow his brains 
out said former gov claude r kirk jr who is challenging 
martinez in the gop primary 
eagletons missouri constituents apparently were unperturbed 
that he had received shock treatment they sent him back to the 
senate with 60 percent of the vote only two years after he was 
forced off the national ticket headed by george mcgovern his 
stability was not an issue in the campaign 
it was obvious that voters didnt have any lingering concerns 
that needed to be addressed kiley said he was held in high 
regard 
rep jim mcdermott dwash the only psychiatrist in congress 
said any candidate who raises mental health questions about an 
opponent must be grasping for issues candidates should be judged 
by how well they perform under stress not by the medication 
theyre taking he said 
abraham lincoln probably would not have been qualified for the 
presidency if this were a disqualifying problem mcdermott said 
referring to lincolns wellknown bouts of melancholia 
frank mankiewicz who was mcgoverns campaign manager in 1972 
said voters find mental illness a lot less frightening and 
therefore less of a stigma now that it typically is treated with 
medication rather than shock therapy 
he and others say voters generally have become more sympathetic 
to candidates fighting alcoholism depression and other illnesses 
as the problems have become more widely acknowledged in society 
most families have had firsthand experience with such troubles 
kiley said 
and increasingly candidates are opening up to voters and 
counting on their understanding 
kiley cited texas treasurer ann richards a recovering alcoholic 
who won a hardfought democratic gubernatorial primary as a case 
in point voters seem to accept her explanation of her illness and 
treatment kiley said 
chiles is in a similar position he said he has great 
credibility hes widely respected he can talk with great candor 
about this aspect of his background and expect to get the fairest 
possible hearing from voters 
mankiewicz said voters might be less touchy about chiles mental 
health because he is running for state rather than national office 
after all he said the governor of florida doesnt have his 
finger on the button 
