a blues for buddha rca the silencers 
 
the silencers hail from scotland but their engaging eclectic 
sound spans the atlantic ocean mixing highland bagpipes with 
memphis guitars motown rhythms and anthemic choruses that recall 
the irish band u2s better efforts 
lyricistvocalist jimmie oneill puts an original spin on themes 
of love faith and social injustice but it is the musical 
arrangements that make a blues for buddha such a pleasure 
one cut sacred child sets a cajun fiddle against a bo 
diddley beat then blends in those bagpipes while oneill raves on 
in english french and spanish about the reckoning day acoming 
all to delightful effect 
this album was recorded in 1988 and released late last year 
heres hoping for a followup in the near future 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 
the silos rca the silos 
 
the silos prove on the first cut of their selftitled debut 
album that they can rock in the best tradition of southern 
headbanger bands 
but there is more than that to this gainesville fla quintet 
and not all of it is as appealing as that first tune caroline 
chief songwriter walter salashumara produces some pretty 
acoustic guitar tunes and intriguing lyrics rich in visual details 
that are sometimes soothing sometimes disturbing 
but fellow silo bob rupe exerts a rougher more backcountry 
influence that tends toward distortion guitars and repetitive 
raspy wailing 
their collaborations on four of the albums 12 songs are 
occasionally exhilarating as in caroline but frequently 
annoying 
meanwhile the bittersweet rocker im over you cowritten 
by salashumara and nonsilo robert ray is the most commercial 
number in the collection and also one of the best 
