<TEXT>
ponder the plight of the piping plover 
this unassuming sandcolored bird already considered an 
endangered species is struggling to make its home in the urban 
jungle 
most humans who visit gateway national recreation area in the 
borough of queens dont even spot the plover which nests well 
camouflaged just an inlet away from brighton beach and coney 
island brooklyn 
but meryl golden a researcher and national park service ranger 
whos considered the pro among ploverwatchers perseveres for 
more than two years she has strived to prevent the plovers 
extinction 
on april 24 the us fish and wildlife service presented a 
northeast region conservation award to gateway for its efforts to 
protect the plover and other endangered birds the least tern the 
common tern and the black skimmer which recently returned to 
gateway after a sevenyear absence 
the average piping plover is 7 inches long with a black ring 
around its neck and a black mark above its eyes it makes a 
twotoned whistle that ornithologists call peep lull 
theyre precious and comical to watch said golden they 
know who i am because i make eye contact with them theyre not 
scared of me 
thirty pairs nest on 2 miles of beach owned partly by the 
national park service and partly by a private apartment complex 
we believe it is the largest concentration of piping plover 
anywhere said golden most beaches this size would have one or 
two pair 
perhaps 145 more pairs live on long island although no one has 
counted golden said its believed 875 pairs live on the atlantic 
coast from north carolina to newfoundland with a few more in the 
great lakes and great plains regions 
the birds enjoy flat shellcovered sparsely vegetated beaches 
when a plover lays its four eggs in a small depression in the sand 
the park service puts up symbolic fencing string flags and 
signs warning that an endangered species is nesting 
the young walk around a few hours after theyre hatched and can 
fly in about 25 days 
instead of placing food in the chicks mouths parents lead them 
to a feast of insects and marine worms unfortunately for the 
plovers one of their feeding areas is the water line where most 
of the human recreation is concentrated said golden 
a mother plover if disturbed tries to convince the predator 
that her wing is broken shell make a lot of noise and lead the 
intruder away from where the young are its quite a convincing 
display said paul nickerson chief of the endangered species 
division of the fish and wildlife services northeast division in 
boston 
last year gateway began banning most recreation on the plovers 
beach during nesting season march 15 through august in 1988 six 
chicks survived long enough to grow plumage and fly in 1989 there 
were 20 said golden 
but the plovers also face other dangers rangers and volunteers 
have removed 3000 pounds of oil from the beach after five spills 
in the past few months 
