<TEXT>
the governments science programs a source of 
technological breakthroughs and national pride are always 
vulnerable to budgetcutters this is the second in a series of 
stories tracking the progress of one portion of this years federal 
budget science spending 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
physicist ellen williams is spending 
less time in her laboratory these days and more in her closetsized 
office shuffling forms and grant applications 
her work on the properties of atoms in solid surfaces could 
someday help advance computer technology it already has won the 
36yearold university of maryland researcher a 1990 award as the 
nations top young female physicist 
but instead she spends long hours at her desk under a 
photograph of nobel prizewinner madame curie tacked to an 
otherwise bare office wall she makes telephone calls writes 
letters and files applications in a search for government and 
corporate financing 
one of the two federal research grants that have kept her in 
business the last few years has expired and the other is being 
slashed nearly in half 
i spend huge amounts of time worrying about money and not 
about science which is unproductive said williams whose 
federal support is shrinking from 100000 to 37500 annually 
id say i have a year left of really good quality research and 
then a serious downward slope unless i find new funding 
williams is not the only scientist grumbling that the 
governments generosity is diminishing from coast to coast and 
from astronomy to zoology scientists performing basic research 
which seeks knowledge regardless of its immediate application are 
complaining that the government is leaving them and the country 
shortchanged 
of this years 12 trillion federal budget 64 billion will be 
spent on scientific research and development 
but only about one in six rampd dollars 114 billion will go 
to basic research which white house science adviser d allan 
bromley calls the heart of our science and technology 
enterprise twothirds of the money is aimed at development 
mainly of weapons while the rest is for applied research devoted 
to advances toward specific goals 
the figures disturb advocates of basic research who rely on 
federal coffers for two of every three dollars they receive the 
competing fields of development and applied research get most of 
their money from nongovernment sources such as corporations which 
tilt their scientific efforts heavily toward developing new 
products 
basic researchers argue that there never has been a time when 
breakthroughs were possible in a broader range of fields from 
robotics to human gene manipulation to global climate changes 
we live in the midst of an explosion of technological and 
theoretical opportunity said douglas e kelly vice president of 
the association of american medical colleges if we do not grasp 
this opportunity other nations stand ready to do so probably at 
our expense 
scientists who perform basic research often poke around in 
obscure areas such as williams study of the properties of atoms 
that even when productive can take decades to bear fruit 
but it is precisely that kind of work that has led to 
unanticipated breakthroughs basic research in the 1940s into the 
magnetic properties of atoms led to magnetic resonance imaging 
used today to examine human organs without surgery the emerging 
field of biotechnology owes its existence to scientists decades ago 
who with no practical goals in mind began tinkering with living 
cells 
the white house and congress aware of such longterm payoffs 
have treated basic research relatively kindly in recent budgets 
the governments annual 150 billion deficits have pinched all 
federal spending limiting many domestic programs to less than 5 
percent growth per year yet federal basic research spending will 
grow this year by 7 percent over 1989 levels in his proposed 1991 
budget president bush wants to boost basic research expenditures 
to 124 billion a 9 percent increase 
basic research advocates however say the dollars still fall 
short 
you really need to look at it not in terms of how weve done 
in the past but in terms of what the research opportunities are 
said david moore executive secretary of the ad hoc group fo 
medical research funding a coalition of about 140 universities 
science societies and voluntary health organizations 
when moore and others visit capitol hill they compete with 
lobbyists for housing veterans and other programs whose 
beneficiaries far outnumber the nations 218000 scientists and 
engineers 
science and technology in the budget are vulnerable and in 
direct competition with programs with very active and very vocal 
constituencies white house adviser bromley told a recent 
washington gathering of scientists 
once congress chooses an amount to be spent on science 
lawmakers then decide how to distribute the money basic research 
advocates cringe when they find themselves vying with projects such 
as the 30 billion space station which attract lots of political 
support and large amounts of money 
megaprojects like the space station have a political life of 
their own driven first by the goal of the project and second by a 
group of political actors who stand to benefit by the placement of 
that project said kenneth kay who lobbies congress for research 
universities and corporations 
there isnt that momentum for the 50000 grant or the 
microscope that some researcher needs he said 
scientists performing basic research even compete with each 
other 
the national science foundation and the national institutes of 
health the governments major agencies for financing 
nongovernment scientists provided money for less than 30 percent 
of the 47000 grant proposals they received in 1989 an alltime 
low percentage 
</TEXT>
