<TEXT>
particles called colloids apparently can 
attach themselves to or encase bits of toxic elements and allow 
them to flow for long distances in water researchers said 
a los alamos national laboratory study suggests colloids could 
confound conventional means of predicting how far pollutants travel 
through ground water 
that in turn means some hazards might have been underestimated 
colloids probably play a more important role than people 
expected in the past said wilfred polzer of the labs earth and 
environmental science division one of the studys coauthors 
the colloids which might be composed of silica or various 
minerals are so small that a powerful microscope is needed to see 
them and so light that they do not settle out of water 
the study published in the journal environmental science and 
technology concerned two radioactive elements plutonium and 
americium but william penrose the studys lead author said the 
phenomenon potentially could affect an array of hazardous and 
radioactive pollutants pesticides and heavy metals 
no one knows how widespread colloids are because nobody has 
routinely looked for them said penrose their existence in ground 
water was unknown until a few years ago and there still is little 
data penrose said 
the study underscores the importance of determining whether 
colloids are present at waste sites throughout the country penrose 
and polzer said 
</TEXT>
