<TEXT>
securities and exchange commission chairman 
richard breeden told a house panel he supports efforts to curb 
penny stock fraud but fears legislation being considered may cause 
as many problems as it solves 
penny stocks are lowcost securities usually trading for less 
than 3 a share that are typically used to raise capital for new 
or small companies they are not listed on stock exchanges and thus 
reliable uptotheminute information about them is hard to obtain 
that makes penny stocks prone to fraud by unscrupulous traders 
and promoters 
the penny stock reform act of 1990 introduced earlier this 
month by rep edward markey dmass would implement several 
reforms they include beefing up the secs power to bar crooked 
promoters and consultants from pushing highly speculative stocks on 
unsophisticated investors and requiring that all penny stocks trade 
through an automated stock quote system 
the energy and commerce committees finance subcommittee which 
markey chairs heard testimony on the bill wednesday supporters of 
all or most of the bills provisions included us attorney dee 
benson of utah and susan e bryant administrator of the oklahoma 
securities department and president of the north american 
securities administrators association a statelevel regulators 
group 
but breeden said that while the sec supports the proposed 
legislations goals there are a number of specific areas where 
the bill as presently drafted create some problems we think it 
would be better to avoid 
unscrupulous penny stock brokers can evade sec banishment from 
the securities business by calling themselves promoters or 
consultants which the sec has no authority to regulate 
to close that loophole the bill would redefine who is a person 
associated with a broker or dealer breeden said the 
legislative language was too broad however and would force 
brokerdealers to register all their officers and other employees 
and maybe even their accountants and lawyers 
that point was supported by another witness john f guion 
president of the associated of publicly traded companies a group 
of 800 concerns whose stock is traded overthecounter 
breeden also criticized a provision to bar socalled blank 
check stock issues which seek investors money without a 
specific business plan or purpose and blind pool penny stocks 
which seek mergers and acquisitions in a specific industry or line 
of business 
what appears to be a simple solution could have costly and 
undesirable side effects breeden said noting that the provision 
could impose added responsibilities on the sec without additional 
resources 
he also said the provision could inhibit legitimate venture 
capital efforts in the real estate oil and gas exploration and 
equipment leasing industries 
rep matthew j rinaldo rnj the subcommittees ranking 
republican and a cosponsor of the bill expressed concerns about 
weakening the legislation 
we want a strong bill we want this practice to a halt said 
rinaldo adding and i dont think were going to be able to do 
it with a weakened piece of legislation 
breeden spent much of his testimony lobbying for passage of the 
securities law enforcement remedies act a market reform bill 
pending before the full house it would give the sec powers it 
never had before including the authority to impose civil fines of 
up to 500000 and halt alleged illegal activity without first 
obtaining a court order 
that bill would enhance the commissions enforcement power in 
all types of cases and they would prove especially valuable in 
combating penny stock fraud said breeden 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

