<TEXT>
the costs of the exxon valdez oil spill 
should be measured not only in dead otters and oiled birds but in 
neglected children broken families and shaken communities 
environmentalists said in a report 
the report timed for release on the day of the annual exxon 
shareholder meeting in houston includes comments by more than 120 
alaskans from hearings held by a citizens commission in november at 
cordova kodiak old harbor homer and anchorage 
the human impacts of the oil spill have largely been ignored 
but theyre continuing doug miller director of the national 
wildlife federations alaska office said wednesday 
the federation was one of the sponsors of the report which 
criticizes exxon for ignoring the human costs of the march 24 
1989 spill and calls on it to help pay for social services 
exxon spokesman jim robertson in anchorage said company 
officials had not had time to read the report to respond to it 
members of the citizens commission said residents around the 
sound reported increased alcoholism domestic violence child abuse 
and neglect 
it certainly wasnt just a wildlife disaster said 
conservationist celia hunter people were totally torn out of 
their whole way of life its a catastrophe like a hurricane 
many in the affected communities made money from the cleanup 
boom receiving high wages from exxon to scrub beaches but 
such spillionaires created envy and anger in the communities 
the commission visited hunter said 
