native corporation said akhiok villagers still were afraid of 
catching and eating seafood activities at the center of their 
communal life and cleaning up beaches he said has been a 
frustrating substitute for fishing 
the state reported wednesday that 80 percent of the shoreline 
sites inspected by a team preparing this seasons cleanup of the 
exxon valdez spill still have oil on them 
most of the 481 sites surveyed in prince william sound and the 
gulf of alaska were lightly or very lightly oiled while 12 percent 
were moderately oiled and 6 percent heavily oiled the alaska 
department of environmental conservation reported 
the survey was conducted this month by state and federal 
agencies exxon and alaska native landowners the groups 
conclusions will be used to help determine what kind of treatment 
should be applied to the beaches this summer 
there is still a lot of oil present either on the surface or 
beneath it and we need to choose the right tools and stick with 
them until the job is done said department commissioner dennis 
kelso 
