<TEXT>
a housing developer on thursday announced plans 
to build an americanstyle suburban residential complex in moscow 
to meet the needs of foreign businessmen frustrated by the soviet 
unions scarce and lowquality housing 
the 130million project will bring a taste of western comfort 
to 80 acres of rolling land near two villages of log cabins on the 
northwest outskirts of moscow according to chris senie secretary 
of senie kerschner international housing ltd 
the project is a joint venture with a collective farm adjacent 
to the site the land is being leased from the collective farm 
the first of the 528 townhouse units are to be completed in 
1991 the development will include amenities such as an indoor 
swimming pool a medical clinic a gymnasium and stores senie said 
the units will rent for about 50000 a year on sixyear leases 
which is comparable to the costs foreign companies pay for 
comparable housing if they can find any available senie said 
although the complex will have guard patrols and its stores will 
accept only hard currency the developers dont want it to be a 
foreign ghetto twenty percent of the units are to be occupied 
by soviet employees of foreign companies 
senie said residents of the adjacent villages will be allowed to 
use the athletic facilities at times and they will have free access 
to a lake that borders the project 
theres no question the project is going to impact their lives 
greatly he said 
the developers also are assisting the collective farm in 
completing a 60acre greenhouse complex senie said 
companies that have reserved units at the complex include 
british airways nichimen of japan and philips of the netherlands 
senie said eighty percent of the units will be rented for hard 
currency and the units for soviets will be rented in rubles 
the construction is to be managed by finnstroi of finland 
using soviet materials where possible and 70 percent soviet 
workers senie said construction costs work out to about 90 a 
square foot building such a development in the united states costs 
about 72 a square foot he said 
zane yost the projects architect said he hopes the 
threestory clapboardstyle buildings will demonstrate the latest 
housing techniques to the soviets 
that he said could be a reparation for unfortunate housing 
ideas that the soviets once learned from the united states he said 
he asked a soviet official one time why so much of the countrys 
postwar housing was in concrete highrise buildings the official 
replied because americans told us to do it that way 
</TEXT>
