<TEXT>
a federal judge dismissed one count of a lawsuit 
thursday accusing the chicago board of trade of illegally 
manipulating soybean prices prompting the exchange and its 
farmgroup adversary to claim victory 
the ruling by us district judge george marovich means the 
american agriculture movement inc cannot sue the board of trade 
based on alleged violations of the commodity exchange act 
but it allows the washingtonbased farmers group to proceed with 
three other counts in the lawsuit alleging antitrust violations 
breach of fiduciary duty and gross negligence 
the lawsuit stems from the board of trades unusual july 11 
order last year requiring traders to reduce their holdings in 
contracts for july delivery of soybeans the result was a steep 
drop in soybean prices on the cash and futures markets 
the board of trade the worlds largest soybean futures market 
issued the order to force the italian company ferruzzi finanziaria 
spa to reduce its soybean holdings the exchange said the large 
holdings threatened to cause a sharp artificial increase in prices 
ferruzzi has denied it was attempting to corner the soybean 
market 
the american agriculture movement filed its classaction lawsuit 
against the board of trade and its officers in november it 
contended the emergency order was illegal and caused us farmers 
to lose more than 100 million on the value of their soybeans 
the count dismissed by marovich the first of four counts in 
the lawsuit declared that farmers like futures brokers and their 
clients have legal standing to sue the exchange based on alleged 
violations of the commodity exchange act marovich disagreed 
the board of trade which had sought to have the entire lawsuit 
dismissed said in a statement that marovich had dismissed the 
major count of the complaint 
we believe that the courts action is further vindication of 
the propriety of our action said exchange chairman karsten 
mahlmann 
mahlmann noted that inquiries by the federal commodity futures 
trading commission and the general accounting office had found no 
wrongdoing by the board of trade 
but john arens a lawyer for the american agriculture movement 
in fayetteville ark said the first count was a throwaway 
arens said the meat of the lawsuit is in the second count which 
accuses the exchange its officers and their trading firms of 
conspiring to restrain soybean trading and fix prices 
the third count alleges exchange officers breached their 
fiduciary duties and the fourth count alleges they acted with gross 
negligence and wanton disregard for market users 
marovich said in his ruling he would entertain a motion from the 
exchange for a summary judgement which is similar to a dismissal 
but which cannot be made until the case is ready to go to trial 
</TEXT>
