mcdonnell douglas corp will cut 3000 jobs 
this summer mainly administrators and nonproduction workers to 
stem losses at its douglas aircraft unit the company said thursday 
in its first quarter report last week the st louisbased 
aerospace company said it had an operating loss of 84 million at 
douglas aircraft twice as big a deficit as in firstquarter 1989 
long beachbased douglas is home to the md80 jetliner and where 
the md11 jetliner and c17 cargo plane are being developed 
employment rose from about 15000 people in 1984 to 50000 today as 
orders for the twinengine md80 surged and the other planes were 
developed 
the bottom line is weve got to reduce costs because the 
performance has not been up to expectations said spokesman john 
thom 
the layoffs will come primarily from staff and support 
functions as opposed to the production side of things thom said 
an examination will get under way soon to see where people are 
needed what kind of shifting will take place 
thom said the cuts had been under discussion for some time and 
were not a reaction to thursdays proposal by defense secretary 
dick cheney to buy only 120 of the c17 longrange transport planes 
instead of the 210 originally planned the move is designed to save 
119 billion over the life of the program 
the md11 and c17 are nearing the end of their development 
phases and some staff reassignments would have been expected in 
any case the md11 is undergoing flight tests and certifications 
the third of the threeengine jumbo jets flew for the first time 
thursday the c17 will fly in 1991 
the company said it would try to transfer some workers who lose 
their jobs into production slots but said an undetermined number 
of people would lose their jobs workers not only in long beach but 
in the companys other operations in the united states and canada 
will be affected 
mcdonnell douglas officials discussed the poor performance at 
douglas aircraft at the companys annual meeting monday but made 
no mention of upcoming layoffs 
fourteen months after a sweeping reorganization in long beach 
mcdonnell officials said theyre still waiting for results 
we are at bottom said john mcdonnell chairman and chief 
executive officer but we really see it as a longterm 
investment we did not expect to see results in 1989 i would 
expect we are not going to see 1990 as bad as 1989 
