<TEXT>
the governments plan to cut production of 
the northrop b2 stealth bomber nearly in half would hurt suppliers 
first but eventually would stunt northrops workforce the company 
said thursday 
defense secretary dick cheney on thursday outlined to congress 
proposed cuts aimed at saving 348 billion through 1997 partly by 
purchasing 75 b2 bombers instead of the 132 originally planned and 
delaying the start of production of advanced tactical fighters 
cheneys proposal predicated on a view of a diminishing soviet 
military threat helps trim the pentagon budget by targeting a 
program in which each aircraft would cost taxpayers 530 million 
northrop employs 12000 people on the b2 project including 
about 1700 who work on assembling the radarevading bomber in 
palmdale calif 
stealth bomber subcontractors and suppliers across the nation 
employ 30000 to 40000 workers said tony cantafio a northrop 
spokesman 
production of five b2s was proposed in the fiscal 1991 budget 
at a cost of 55 billion under the new plan only two jets would 
be built that year 
the immediate effect may be felt by suppliers and 
subcontractors around the country said cantafio 
from an employment standpoint at northrop there wont be an 
immediate effect 
northrop still will need to hire several hundred more workers 
for the palmdale plant because of prior orders cantafio said 
however cheneys proposal would halve production in peak years to 
12 from 24 aircraft 
obviously in the long run we wont build up our employment to 
the original schedule cantafio said 
