<TEXT>
police said they are investigating a former 
president of a finance firm for suspected insider trading the 
first such investigation since japan tightened laws against insider 
trading last year 
a spokesman for the tokyo metropolitan police department on 
thursday said the investigation focused on hironori mito 56 
former president of chiyoda finance a mediumsized financing firm 
in tokyo 
mito is suspected to have acted on inside information in 
purchasing 7000 shares of nisshin steamship co a japanese 
shipping operator in june 1989 the purchase was made a few days 
ahead of the companys announcement of terms of a new share 
allotment said the spokesman who spoke on condition he not be 
identified 
the police spokesman refused to provide further details saying 
only that the investigation had begun 
an official of nisshin steamship refused to comment 
the nihon keizai shimbun a major japanese economic newspaper 
quoted shiro shikai chief of the companys general affairs 
department as saying that only chairman harunori takahashi and 
three other top officials had known of the allotment of new shares 
before the companys official announcement june 16 1989 
it was the first such investigation launched by police since 
japan last year enacted a stricter law against benefiting from 
inside information in the trading of stocks the united states had 
pressured tokyo to bring its law in line with those in other world 
financial centers 
under the new law enacted in january 1989 those convicted of 
insider trading will face up to six months imprisonment or a fine 
of up to 500000 yen about 3160 previous violations were 
treated as civil offenses though few cases ever came to light 
police investigators on wednesday searched five locations 
including mitos home the offce of chiyoda finance and a new japan 
securities cos branch office in tokyo where mito allegedly 
bought the shares under a womans name police collected an 
unspecified number of documents the spokesman said 
the tokyo stock exchange and the finance ministry investigated 
the alleged insider trading last june but failed to find evidence 
of insider trading according to exchange officials 
